Data Sources

The image data we used come from the ISIC 2019 Challenge training Dataset. The datasets that make up this set are the BCN_20000 Dataset, the HAM10000 Dataset, and the MSK Dataset.

Image Data Processing

All images fed into our model underwent the following processing: first we resize the image, then we run a noise removal function that eliminates hair and other such noise, then we run a masking predictor to essentially blackout the skin surrounding the lesion, and then we normalize the RGB values. Your input image will undergo the same such processing before being fed into our model. Please also note that our backend ensures that your image is not stored anywhere to maintain ultimate privacy.

Image Augmentation

Before training our model, we augmented our training data using layered color, geometric, and warping augmentations, shown below. This was our method of making our model more robust to noise in input data and variations in image quality. This also serves to improve performance metrics by creating synthetic data for the underrepresented malignant class.

Model Architecture

Our model is an ensemble of 5 hyperparameter-tuned and fine-tuned transfer learning models well suited for image classification tasks like ours: Mobilenet, Densenet121, Densenet169, Nasnetmobile, and SENet154. We utilized pruning methods to select the best 5 models out of the initial 22 we had trained and tested. We ensembled the 5 chosen models using a Logistic Regression metalearner.
